Jeffrey H. Smulyan Joins USC Board of Trustees


BY Gilien Silsby January 14, 2002



 
Jeffrey H. Smulyan, a USC alumnus and chairman of Emmis Commun-ications Corp., has been elected to the board of trustees. 
 Photo by Tony Valanis

Jeffrey H. Smulyan, chairman, president and principal shareholder of Emmis Communications Corp., an Indianapolis-based broadcasting company, has been elected to the USC board of trustees.
Smulyan is a presidential associate and a member of the board of councilors of the USC Annenberg School for Communication and the USC Law School. He is past regional director of USC’s Midwest Alumni Club and past president of the Indianapolis Alumni Club. He earned both his bachelor’s degree and a law degree from USC.
In announcing Smulyan’s election, USC President Steven B. Sample said: “Jeff Smulyan is a dedicated and energetic addition to our board of trustees. As an alumnus who served as class president in his senior year on campus, he has a deep commitment to this university and its mission. We look forward to his leadership.”
Smulyan founded Emmis Communications Corp in 1981. Today, the company – which went public in 1994 – boasts $650 million in annual sales. It owns and operates 23 radio stations in the nation’s largest markets, including New York City, Los Angeles (KZLA and KPWR – “Power 106”) and Chicago. It also operates 15 television stations in cities stretching from Orlando to Honolulu. Emmis also owns and operates six city and regional magazines, including Los Angeles, Texas Monthly and Atlanta.
Last year, Smulyan received the National Association of Broadcasters’ National Radio Award and as Radio Ink’s “Radio Executive of the Year.” 
“It is a great honor to be elected to the USC board of trustees,” Smulyan said. “I have such fond memories of the university from both my undergraduate and law school days. As a current USC parent, I have been very excited about the remarkable achievements that the university has made under Dr. Sample. It is with much pride that I accept this.”
After earning his J.D. degree from USC Law School in 1972, Smulyan entered the radio business, operating two stations in Indianapolis and Omaha before forming Emmis. As principal shareholder of Emmis, Smulyan led a group to purchase the Seattle Mariners baseball team in 1989. He sold the club three years later. 
Smulyan, a former director of the National Association of Broadcasters and former chairman of the board of directors of the Radio Advertising Bureau, serves as chair of the Central Indiana Corporate Partnership, a consortium of CEOs from the largest central Indiana corporations.
Smulyan also sits on the board of trustees of Ball State University and the board of directors of Finish Line Inc., an athletic apparel company. He is a member of the American, Indiana and Federal Communications bar associations and has served on numerous civic boards and committees.
In 1994 he was named by the White House as U.S. ambassador to head the delegation to the Plenipotentiary Conference of the International Telecommunications Union. 
A cum laude graduate of USC, Smulyan earned a B.A. in history and telecommunications in 1969. 
Smulyan enjoys sports, politics and reading. He lives in Indianapolis and has two children: Bradley, 19, and Cari, 21, a senior majoring in theater at USC.





